{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}} {{Featured article}} {{Infobox film | name = Asmara Moerni | image = Asmara Moerni cover.jpg | image_size = | border = yes | alt = A black, red, and white book cover | caption = Cover of the novelisation | director = [[Rd Ariffien]] | producer = Ang Hock Liem | screenplay = [[Saeroen]] | narrator = | starring ={{Plainlist| * [[Adnan Kapau Gani]] * [[Djoewariah]] *S. Joesoef }} | music = | cinematography = | editing = | studio = [[Union Films]] | distributor = | released = {{Film date|df=yes|1941|04|29|Dutch East Indies}} | runtime = | country = [[Dutch East Indies]] | language = Indonesian | budget = | gross = }}
'''''Asmara Moerni''''' ({{IPA-id|asˈmara mʊrˈni|}}; [[EYD|Perfected Spelling]]: '''''Asmara Murni'''''; [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] for ''True Love'') is a 1941 romance film from the [[Dutch East Indies]] (now [[Indonesia]]) directed by [[Rd Ariffien]] and produced by Ang Hock Liem for [[Union Films]]. Written by [[Saeroen]], the film followed a doctor who falls in love with his maid, as well as her failed romance with a fellow villager. Starring [[Adnan Kapau Gani]], [[Djoewariah]], and S. Joesoef, the [[black-and-white]] film was cast and advertised to cater to the growing [[native Indonesians|native]] intelligentsia. Despite mixed reviews, it was a commercial success. As with most films of the Indies, ''Asmara Moerni'' may be [[lost film|lost]].
== Plot == After four years of doing his residency in [[Singkawang]], Borneo, Dr. Pardi ([[Adnan Kapau Gani]]) returns to [[Java]] to open a practice. Before then, he goes to Cigading to visit his family and give them souvenirs. Upon arrival he is stunned to find that his family's maid Tati ([[Djoewariah]]), who had been his childhood playmate, is now a grown and beautiful woman. He secretly begins to fawn over Tati, although he does not tell her the reason. When Pardi's mother tells him he should marry quickly, he refuses all of her suggested brides. He says only that he already has someone in mind, aware that his mother would never approve an inter-class marriage with the maid.
Tati's fiancé, Amir (S. Joesoef), is jealous of all the attention that Tati is receiving, which leaves her no time for him. He plans to leave Cigading for the capital, Batavia (today [[Jakarta]]), where he will find work. Tati, upon learning this, joins him. She lives at her aunt's home in the city, making a living by washing clothes, while he finds lodging with a local man and learns to drive a ''[[pedicab|becak]]'' (pedicab). Together they begin saving for their wedding. Unknown to them, Pardi has cut short his time in Cigading to move to Batavia, both to begin his new job and to find Tati.
Days before the wedding, Amir is playing his flute when he is approached by a singer known as Miss Omi, who asks him to join her troupe on an international tour. Amir refuses, even after Omi hires him to drive her around the city in an attempt to convince him. After dropping Omi off, Amir is approached by a man who asks him to deliver a package; however, before he can deliver the package Amir is arrested and charged with smuggling [[opium]].
When Amir does not return, Tati and her aunt are worried: as Tati saw Amir with Omi, she fears that the two have run away together. Heartbroken, she intends to return to Cigading. When she and her aunt visit their boss, Abdul Sidik, they unknowingly pass Pardi{{snds}}Abdul Sidik's doctor. Upon returning home, Pardi calls Abdul Sidik and asks him to take Tati in as if she were his daughter and educate her. Tati is a fast learner, and is soon comparable to any woman from a wealthy family.
After being held eighteen months without trial, Amir is released and returned to Batavia. He is unable to find Tati, leaving him to wander the streets. Omi spots him, and again she asks him to play with her troupe. Amir agrees, and soon newspapers are filled with advertisements touting his name. Spotting one, Tati and Abdul Sidik go to a performance, only to learn that Amir was the victim of a car accident. At the hospital, where Amir is being treated by Pardi, Tati learns the truth behind Amir's absence. On his deathbed, Amir asks Pardi to take care of Tati; the two are later married.{{efn|Derived from the novelisation published by Kolff-Buning.}}
== Production == {{multiple image | footer = Promotional stills of [[Djoewariah]] (left) and [[Adnan Kapau Gani]], the stars of ''Asmara Moerni'' | image1 = Asmara Moerni Tati.jpg | alt1 = Djoewariah, female lead of ''Asmara Moerni'' | width1 = 200
| image2 = Asmara Moerni Pardi.jpg | alt2 = Adnan Kapau Gani, male lead of ''Asmara Moerni'' | width2= 200 }} ''Asmara Moerni'' was directed by [[Rd Ariffien]], a former journalist who had been active in the [[Indonesian National Awakening|nationalist]] and [[labour movement]]s before turning to theatre.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=232}} He had joined [[Union Films]]&nbsp;– the company behind ''Asmara Moerni''&nbsp;– in 1940, making his debut with ''[[Harta Berdarah]]'' (''Bloody Treasure'').{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Rd Ariffien}} Union's head Ang Hock Liem produced,{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Asmara Moerni}} while the story was written by journalist [[Saeroen]],{{sfn|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, Sampoerna: 'Asmara Moerni'}} who had joined Union after commercial success on [[Albert Balink]]'s ''[[Terang Boelan]]'' (''Full Moon'', 1937) and with the production house [[Tan's Film]].{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Saeroen}}
The [[black-and-white]] film starred Adnan Kapau Gani, Djoewariah, and S. Joesoef.<ref>{{harvnb|Filmindonesia.or.id, Asmara Moerni}}; {{harvnb|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, (untitled)}}</ref> It was the feature film debut of Gani and Joesoef,<ref>{{harvnb|Biran|2009|pp=262–63}}; {{harvnb|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, (untitled)}}</ref> while Djoewariah had been on Union's payroll since ''[[Bajar dengan Djiwa]]'' (''Pay with Your Soul'') the preceding year.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djuariah}}
At the time there was a growing movement to attract native intelligentsia, educated at schools run by the [[Dutch East Indies|Dutch colonial government]], and convince them to view domestic films, which were generally considered to be of much lower quality than imported Hollywood productions.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=260}} This was blamed, in part, on the dominance of theatrically trained actors and crew.{{efn|This included [[Roekiah]], [[Kartolo]], [[Fifi Young]], [[Astaman]], [[Ratna Asmara]], and [[Andjar Asmara]]. See {{harvtxt|Biran|2009|p=204}}.}} As such, Ariffien invited Gani, at the time a medical doctor and a prominent member of the nationalist movement, to join the cast. Although some nationalists considered Gani's involvement in ''Asmara Moerni'' as besmirching the independence movement, Gani considered it necessary: he believed audiences needed to have higher opinions of domestic film productions.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=262–63}}
== Release and reception == ''Asmara Moerni'' was premiered on 29 April 1941 at Orion Theatre in Batavia; the crowds were mostly [[native Indonesians|natives]] and [[Chinese Indonesians|ethnic Chinese]].{{sfn|Bataviaasch Nieuwsblad 1941, Filmaankondigingen}} Rated for all ages, advertising for the film emphasised Gani's education and Joesoef's upper-class background.{{sfn|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, (untitled)}} It was also advertised as breaking away from the conventional standards of stage theatre, such as music, which were omnipresent in the contemporary film industry.{{sfn|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, (untitled)}} By August 1941 it was screened in [[Singapore]], then part of the [[Straits Settlements]], and billed as a "modern Malay drama".{{sfn|The Straits Times 1941, (untitled)}} A novelisation was published later in 1941 by the [[Yogyakarta]]-based Kolff-Buning.{{sfn|Saeroen|1941|p=1}}
The film was a commercial success,{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=262–63}} though reviews were mixed. An anonymous review for the ''[[Bataviaasch Nieuwsblad]]'' found the film "fascinating",{{efn|Original: "''... boeiend ...''"}} with good acting,{{sfn|Bataviaasch Nieuwsblad 1941, Filmaankondigingen}} though another review for the same paper found that, though the film was better than contemporary works such as ''[[Pantjawarna]]'' and ''[[Sorga Ka Toedjoe]]'', its claim to abandon stage standards was to be taken "with a pinch of salt".{{efn|Original: "... ''moet men dit wel met een korreltje zout''"}}{{sfn|Bataviaasch Nieuwsblad 1941, Iets over de Maleische Film}} A review from the [[Surabaya]]-based ''[[Soerabaijasch Handelsblad]]'' found the film full of drama, describing it as "Western [[Motif (narrative)|motifs]], played in the native environment, with a specifically Sundanese situation".{{efn|Original: "... ''een geheel naar westersche motieven opgezet scenario, spelend in het inheemsche milieu met specifiek Soendaneesche decors.''"}}{{sfn|Soerabaijasch Handelsblad 1941, Sampoerna: 'Asmara Moerni'}}
== Legacy == After ''Asmara Moerni'', Union produced a further three films;{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=233}} only one, ''[[Wanita dan Satria]]'', was by Rd Ariffien, who left the company soon after,{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=263}} as did Saeroen.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=234}} Gani did not act in any further films,{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=262–63}} but instead returned to the nationalist movement. During the [[Indonesian National Revolution]] (1945–49) he became known as a smuggler, and after independence became a government minister.{{sfn|Mufid 2012, Menyelundup untuk Kemakmuran Republik}} In November 2007 Gani was made a [[National Hero of Indonesia]].{{sfn|Suara Merdeka 2007, Presiden Anugerahkan Gelar}} Djoewariah continued to act until the 1950s, when she migrated to theatre after receiving a series of increasingly minor roles.{{sfn|Filmindonesia.or.id, Djuariah}}
''Asmara Moerni'' was screened as late as November 1945.{{sfn|Soeara Merdeka 1945, Pilem}} The film is likely [[lost film|lost]]. Movies in the Indies were recorded on highly flammable [[nitrate film]], and after a fire destroyed much of [[Produksi Film Negara]]'s warehouse in 1952, old films shot on nitrate were deliberately destroyed.{{sfn|Biran|2012|p=291}} As such, American visual anthropologist [[Karl G. Heider]] suggests that all Indonesian films from before 1950 are lost.{{sfn|Heider|1991|p=14}} However, JB Kristanto's ''Katalog Film Indonesia'' (''Indonesian Film Catalogue'') records several as having survived at [[Sinematek Indonesia]]'s archives, and film historian [[Misbach Yusa Biran]] writes that several Japanese propaganda films have survived at the [[Netherlands Government Information Service]].{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=351}}
