{{for|the Warner Bros contract actor|Charles Emmett Mack}} [[File:Moran and Mack Two Black Crows 1929.JPG|thumb|Moran and Mack in character in 1929.]] '''Charles Sellers''' ([[White Cloud, Kansas]], November 22, 1888 – January 11, 1934<ref>https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/19789</ref>) was an American [[minstrel show]] performer who worked in [[blackface]] under the stage name '''Charles Mack'''. He worked with [[John Swor]] and later [[George Moran (comedian)|George Moran]] as the [[Two Black Crows]].<ref>Vaudeville old & new: an encyclopedia of variety performances in America 0415938538 Frank Cullen, Florence Hackman, Donald McNeilly - 2007 -"... known professionally as Charles Mack, although a few sources confuse him with another actor, Charles Emmett Mack ... However, until the advent of Amos 'n' Andy, Two Black Crows was the most popular blackface comedy act in America .."</ref>
==Biography== He married Marian Robinson. They divorced in 1931.<ref>{{cite news |author= |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title=Charles Mack Sues Wife. Actor Seeks Divorce, While She Plans to File Cross Bill |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/07/24/archives/charles-mack-sues-wife-actor-seeks-divorce-while-she-plans-to-file.html |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=July 24, 1931 |accessdate=2015-03-22 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= |agency= |title=Mack Asks a Divorce. Decision Is Reserved in Suit Brought by Radio Performer |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/24/archives/mack-asks-a-divorce-decision-is-reserved-in-suit-brought-by-radio.html |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=October 24, 1931 |accessdate=2015-03-22 }}</ref> He later married Myrtle Buckley on July 24, 1932 in [[San Diego, California]].<ref>{{cite news |author= |agency= |title=Charles Mack Marries |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/07/25/archives/charles-mack-marries.html |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date= July 25, 1932 |accessdate=2015-03-22 }}</ref>
He died on January 11, 1934 in [[Mesa, Arizona]] in a car accident. He was driving when a [[Blowout (tire)|tire blew out]] and the car overturned several times, his wife was injured but survived. Also in the car were his daughter, Mary Jane Mack; [[George Moran (comedian)|George Moran]] and [[Mack Sennett]]. The funeral arrangements were made by [[W. C. Fields]] and [[William S. Hart]]. Hart gave the eulogy and [[Noah Beery]] sang.<ref>{{cite news |author= |agency= |title=Mack's Funeral At Los Angeles, Widow Decides |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=January 13, 1934 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= |agency= |title=W. S. Hart To Hold Mack Funeral Rites. Former Two-Gun Hero of Screen to Pay Last Tribute to Noted Comedian |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1934/01/14/archives/w-s-hart-to-hold-mack-funeral-rites-former-twogun-hero-of-screen-to.html |quote= |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=January 14, 1934 |accessdate=2015-03-22 }}</ref> He was buried in [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park]] in [[Glendale, California]].<ref>{{cite news |author= |agency= |title=Charles E. Mack Buried. William S. Hart Gives Eulogy and Noah Beery Sings at Service |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1934/01/16/archives/charles-e-mack-buried-william-s-hart-gives-eulogy-and-noah-beery.html |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=January 16, 1934 |accessdate=2015-03-22 }}</ref> His estate was valued at $50,000 (approximately ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|50000|1934|r=-3}}}} today).<ref>{{cite news |author= |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title=Mack Estate Put at $50,000 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1934/02/07/archives/mack-estate-put-at-50000.html |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=February 7, 1934 |accessdate=2015-03-22 }}</ref>
