{{use mdy dates|date=July 2015}} {{Infobox film | name = The Miracle Woman | image = The Miracle Woman 1931 Poster.jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = theatrical release poster | director = [[Frank Capra]] | producer = [[Harry Cohn]] | writer = Dorothy Howell ''(continuity)'' | screenplay = [[Jo Swerling]] | based on = {{based on|''Bless You Sister''|[[John Meehan (screenwriter)|John Meehan]] and [[Robert Riskin]]}} | starring = [[Barbara Stanwyck]] | music = | cinematography = [[Joseph Walker (cinematographer)|Joseph Walker]] | editing = Maurice Wright | studio = [[Columbia Pictures]] | distributor = Columbia Pictures | released = {{Film date|1931|08|07|''US''}} | runtime = 90 minutes | country = United States | language = English | budget = | gross = }}
'''''The Miracle Woman''''' is a 1931 American [[pre-Code]] [[Christian film]] directed by [[Frank Capra]] and starring [[Barbara Stanwyck]], [[David Manners]], and [[Sam Hardy (actor)|Sam Hardy]]. Based on the play ''Bless You Sister'' by [[John Meehan (screenwriter)|John Meehan]] and [[Robert Riskin]], the film is about a preacher's daughter who becomes disillusioned by the mistreatment of her dying father by his church. Having grown cynical about religion, she teams up with a con man and performs fake miracles for profit. The love and trust of a blind man, however, restores her faith in God and her fellow man. ''The Miracle Woman'' was the second of five film collaborations between Capra with Stanwyck. Produced and distributed by [[Columbia Pictures]], the film was reportedly inspired by the life of [[Aimee Semple McPherson]].<ref name="nytimes">{{cite web|title=The Miracle Woman (1931)|work=The New York Times|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/102467/The-Miracle-Woman/overview|accessdate=January 31, 2013}}</ref>
==Plot== Florence Fallon is outraged when church elders, in order to make way for a younger preacher, fire her minister father after his many years of selfless service. Following her father's death, she tells the congregation what she thinks of their ingratitude and hypocrisy. Her bitter, impassioned speech impresses Bob Hornsby, who convinces her to become a phony [[evangelism|evangelist]] so they can squeeze donations out of gullible believers. Promoted as Sister Fallon, Florence then travels about the country with Bob, who manages her "Temple of Happiness". Soon she attracts a devoted national following, but the religious sham comes tumbling down once she meets and falls in love with John Carson, a blind war veteran. When Florence is blackmailed by Bob, she tells John of her charade. John then puts a plan in motion to expose Hornsby and the organization
==Cast== *[[Barbara Stanwyck]] as Florence Fallon *[[David Manners]] as John Carson *[[Sam Hardy (actor)|Sam Hardy]] as Bob Hornsby *[[Beryl Mercer]] as Mrs Higgins *[[Russell Hopton]] as Bill Welford *[[Charles B. Middleton|Charles Middleton]] as Simpson *[[Eddie Boland]] as Collins *[[Thelma Hill]] as Gussie
